Suppose you have a payment system.

Different ways to pay:

Credit Card

PayPal

UPI

A bad design might look like this:

if(paymentType == "card")
    payByCard();
else if(paymentType == "paypal")
    payByPaypal();
else if(paymentType == "upi")
    payByUPI();

Problems:

Many if-else

Hard to extend

Violates Open/Closed Principle

Strategy pattern solves this by encapsulating algorithms into separate classes.

2️⃣ Core Idea

Instead of if-else, create separate strategy classes.

PaymentStrategy
     |
-----------------------------
|            |              |
CardPay   PayPalPay      UpiPay

uses in 

SortStrategy
   |
QuickSort
MergeSort
HeapSort

===========================================
RatePlanStrategy
   |
-------------------------
|          |            |
Refundable NonRefund  Corporate

Now let’s turn this into a proper interview-level design in C++.

Step 1 — Strategy Interface
class RatePlanStrategy {
public:
    virtual int calculatePrice(int basePrice) = 0;
    virtual ~RatePlanStrategy() {}
};
Step 2 — Concrete Strategies
class RefundablePlan : public RatePlanStrategy {
public:
    int calculatePrice(int basePrice) override {
        return basePrice + 200; // flexible, higher cost
    }
};

class NonRefundablePlan : public RatePlanStrategy {
public:
    int calculatePrice(int basePrice) override {
        return basePrice - 100; // cheaper, no refund
    }
};

class CorporatePlan : public RatePlanStrategy {
public:
    int calculatePrice(int basePrice) override {
        return basePrice - 150; // corporate discount
    }
};
Step 3 — Context (very important)
class PricingEngine {
private:
    RatePlanStrategy* strategy;

public:
    PricingEngine(RatePlanStrategy* s) : strategy(s) {}

    int getFinalPrice(int basePrice) {
        return strategy->calculatePrice(basePrice);
    }
};
Step 4 — Usage (like your system)
int main() {
    RatePlanStrategy* strategy = new RefundablePlan();

    PricingEngine engine(strategy);

    cout << engine.getFinalPrice(1000);
}